<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Express Solicitors (CMI0005)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Express Solicitors (CMI0005)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Key Points</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ensure the Insurance Industry provide access to databases on cases where they make allegations of fraud or d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ishonesty against a Claimant</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ensure that publication of future statistics provided by the Insurance Industry are based in fact and founded evidence and not estimated or based upon assumptions – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">i.e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> number of fraud cases only taken from actual cases where f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">raud is proven by a court</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Prevent Insurers from making pre medical offers</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Prevent insurers from contacting victims to persuade them to make claims </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To ensure that a plan is put together about medical panels along with a full cost and benefit plan for all p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">arties concerned with actual costs and then consult upon the same with all stakeholders again</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To ensure that in all cases medical records are obtained to assist with ensuring record of genuine injury is obtained</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To avoid the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">dumbing down</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> of reporting by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">experts which could mean victims are prejudiced</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Harsher and more visible punishments of founded fraudulent claimants</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Changes to driving laws to effect those most likely to be in road traffic accidents</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Allow a period of several years to see what effect of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">he current changes has on the system as a whole</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction to Express Solicitors</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Our firm specialises in making personal injury claims for victims of accidents and has been established since 2000</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with over 120 staff of which 45 are fee earners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  We have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a caseload of over 4500 across the firm of which 28.5% are road traffic accidents, of which we would estimate 70</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> - 80</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">% have some element of whiplash within the injuries sustained.  We are responding to this consultation on behalf of all of our existing cl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ients and future clients who will be affected by any changes made to the way claims for injuries that have an element of a whiplash injury are made.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over the last 12 months there have been various inquiries under taken by the Transport Select Co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mmittee into the cost of motor insurance and by the MOJ into reducing the number and costs of whiplash claims.  Various proposals were to be considered and following the last inquiry and consultation the government published </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> response to the Transport </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Select Committee’s recommendations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Fraudulent Claims</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In our experience over the last 13 years the number of fraudulent whiplash injury claims we have personally seen are few and far between and a very small minority compared with the number of genuine cla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ims we have handled.  We do not deny that there are claimant’s out there who are not genuine but they are such a small minority that we would question the ethics in changing matters further that will deter and effectively punish further genuine claimants f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rom claiming damages to which they are legally entitled and whilst nothing is being done to ensure that those pursuing the fraudulent claims in the first place are made examples of and whilst insurers (the ABI) refuse to ensure their members engage in data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sharing to allow claimant representatives to have access to information that may provide early evidence of fraudulent accident claims and put a stop to them before any meaningful costs are incurred.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At the recent Manchester Law Society Autumn PI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Conference a letter from the ABI to the MOJ/TCS was produced which suggested talks between the Claimant and Defendant sectors into data sharing had irretrievably broken down.  However, the MASS chairman had highlighted that this was a falsehood as there wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s one issue out of all the issues being discussed which was a sticking point, which was producing details of previous accidents on the basis that the Claimant’s representatives would use this information to go fishing for new claims.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  This is evidence of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he ABI’s approach to negotiation on such matters and suggests they genuinely do not wish to share data if they are trying to withdraw from negotiations and suggest an irretrievable breakdown based upon one distinct point that could not be agreed and should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> therefore have been considered by the committee rather than being informed that the negotiations had broken down.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">By enforcing a database that provides information on people’s claims histories that is available to both sides at the start of any claim </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will ensure a level playing ground and early detection of key fraud indicators that insurers often refer to when they “detect” a “fraudulent” claim.  This can then ensure that dishonest claims are abandoned early at a minimal cost to both insurer and claim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ant representative and genuine claims can continue.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ABI is very good at producing estimated figures but has consistently failed each and every time to produce actual evidence that 7% of all motor claims being fraudulent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  In our experience the insuran</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ce industry is guilty of perpetrating a myth regarding the number of fraudulent claims and the associated of cost without hard evidence of the number of claims proven to be fraudulent only basing it on an estimate of those detected.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Further the insuranc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e industry continue to contact injured people directly after accidents inviting them to make personal injury claims and offering them compensation without undergoing any medical examination.  Such behaviour should be curtailed through law and as such those</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that might never thought of making a claim because they were not injured or were minimally injured would not be tempted into accepting damages to which they might not actually be entitled.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The response suggests better data is going to be obtained but doe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s not address how this will be obtained.  We would suggest that the starting point would be through the Management Information available on the Claims Portal but even so those claims that thereafter fall out would have to be tracked and individual response</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s obtained from both parties to the claim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, from whom responses may not be provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  The only real way of obtaining information on the number of fraudulent claims are those that are pursued to trial and fraud found as any other claim where such an allegati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on is made does not make it fraudulent unless so proven in a court.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Medical Panels / Accreditation</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We note the reason here is to ensure that Claimant’s medical evidence is independent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and to give a better diagnosis of whiplash injuries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  There seems to hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e been some overlooking of the fact that current evidence is obtained through an independent expert who despite being instructed by the Claimant owes their first and foremost duty to the court.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The suggestion of payment by results is in our experience pla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inly wrong.  For experts to be independent as per their duty to the court they cannot be instructed on a  contingency style basis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and we are not aware of any such experts operating and have not seen any such evidence to back up such an assertion.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be held to be accountable for their evidence if found to be wholly inaccurate through costs sanctions or through breach of duty claims now that expert immunity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has been removed (Jones v </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Kaney</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).  Cases where the evidence is considered questionable by a Def</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">endant is dealt with by questions to the expert and then a request for their own expert evidence.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government suggests a one size fits all type of report for consistency but not all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">claimant’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are the same and not all standardised reports would ensur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e that all of the necessary considerations of a claimant’s injuries, pain, suffering and loss of amenity are covered, this is why so many experts failed to use the standard format that was introduced by the RTA Protocol because it was “dumbed down” and som</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ewhat inadequate at accurately portraying the Claimant’s injuries.  The report cannot and should not become a tick box exe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cise as this fails to address the elements properly which are needed to assess damages for injuries.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The report refers to guidance o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n current best practice but fails to address who would write such guidance and whether they are actually the best person to address the subject.  Medical experts gain their knowledge through their education and then experience it is not appropriate to try </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and curtail that by issuing strict guidelines about how they should form their opinion as that runs the risk of interfering with the same and therefore would infringe the claimant’s right to a fair trial.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The suggestion of reports being made equally avail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">able to both parties and the court is confusing as at present the medical evidence is of no use to a party unless it has been disclosed and proceedings cannot be commenced and damages not awarded unless medical evidence is disclosed and before the court.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Such a panel of experts would need to be widely subscribed to by various types of experts all over the country and the Government should consider a survey of the medical profession generally to see whether or not they would widely subscribe to such a progr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">amme of accreditation and their own cost and whether this in turn would increase their costs of reporting, which in turn would increase the costs of claims</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which is against the core of the proposal which was to reduce the cost of claims</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  If the subscript</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion by experts was not wide then Claimants in particular areas of the country could be prejudiced if there are no experts within a reasonable distance.  It is somewhat premature to suggest such a scheme without addressing whether the medical profession as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a whole would apply and pay to be accredited and pay a subscription to remain so and be audited.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The consultation proposes this only for whiplash injuries and possibly other neck and back injuries described as soft tissue injuries, but what of claimant’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who have more than one injury which includes a whiplash type injury, they would not have to go through panel as their injury is not solely whiplash based and so the new proposed system is also open to being abused as those same fraudulent or exaggerated cl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aimants will simply suggest they also have a further soft tissue injury elsewhere to avoid the panel.  Alternatively, if you impose the panel for someone who has various injuries they could be prejudiced if the panel does not have the right expert for thei</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r other injuries.  If the panel is to remain a consideration it needs very careful consideration to stop any abuses arising but that also ensures that a genuine claimant can be seen by the right experts regardless of the panel.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is very difficult for us</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to respond to a document which is so very thin on actual details of how things may work in reality and without assessing the impact of the actual proposals down to the minute detail no party interested in this consultation can provide a coherent stance ot</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">her than make assumptions, as such the government should put forward how they intend </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to actually achieve this goal so it can be properly considered by insurers, claimant representatives and the medical community in full.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although a panel may be the way for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ward to some degree we believe that more ground work needs to be done to ensure that such an idea is workable in practice and that the above points need to be considered as part of that work.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The insurance industry should accept their part in why evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> when looked at by a person outside the claims industry is questionable because it was the insurance industry who wanted to ensure reduced costs on claims worth less than £10,000.00 by the Claimant not providing an expert with their medical records.  Even </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">now within the new RTA Protocol there is a presumption that records will not be obtained unless the expert considers it necessary.  In that case considering most of the claims involving whiplash are worth less than £10,000.00 and within the RTA Protocol th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ere will be no obtaining of medical records to ensure the Claimant has sought any medical attention in the immediate aftermath of the accident.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Therefore, under the current proposals there would have to be a reversal of this presumption and in all cases m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">edical records should be obtained, thus actually increasing costs by at least £50.00 for each set of records required, depending upon how many medical institutions have been attended.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Small claims Increase</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government has refrained from increasing th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e limit for RTA whiplash claims and we agree that this is the right thing to do.  However, we would argue that this should not be revisited any time soon.  Since 2004 costs in RTA claims worth less than £10,000.00 which will account for most whiplash injur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y claims have been significantly reduced, further reductions were applied in 2010 and then again this year.  The number of claims has also fallen within the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">year 2011/2012 by almost 24,000.00.  However, in the same period 2044 to the present generally prem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iums have increased with a different reason being set out by the insurance industry each time – number of uninsured motorists, number of frauds, number of low speed impacts, solicitors costs.  The government now need to monitor the exact figures from the i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nsurance industry for damages and costs paid out on whiplash claims and ensure that a comparative reduction in those figures from previous years is passed onto motorists which is the core of these proposals rather than increasing insurers revenue and profi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The effect of the current changes will need to be monitored for a number of years to ensure that older claims are removed from the picture and so the impact of the changes can properly be assessed before any further changes are considered which will on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly benefit insurers, if the savings are not passed on, at the expense of the injured person who will then be looking to the government to pay them whilst off sick and nurse them better without being able to recover the NHS charges from the insurer.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The pas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sing on of costs – reductions allegedly already show 12% reduction but there was no supporting evidence of that in the report and that could be a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">non comparable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  A proper comparison that the government should consider is a person’s renewal quote an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d not quotes from comparison sites that would not provide the exact same cover.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Driving Changes</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We agree that changes need to be made to our driving system including age limits </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as in our experience a lot of cases involving fatalities or serious </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">injuries do tend to involve young drivers with young passengers in the late evening and such changes to the system including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mandatory driving lessons with a skilled instructor for a definite period and a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">post test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> course with restrictions on driving may b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e warranted but we also have to ensure that those responsible young adults who need their vehicles late at night also have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the ability to drive as per their need.   We also believe that better policing of uninsured and unlicensed drivers and foreign driver</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s who reside in the UK but have failed to take a UK driving test should also be considered, perhaps the insurance industry should ensure this through the access to the DVLA which will ensure those that should not be on the roads are removed safely and thei</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r vehicles, where not insured are destroyed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Of course developments in engineering for cars will also continue to help prevent accidents into the future but we need to ensure the public does not become reliant on the intelligence of their vehicle at the e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">xpense of not reacting to a hazard.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Decembe</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font